<h2>What this partner does</h2>
<p>Bring a specific field photo, Google Earth view, or geological map of your chosen Chennai-area location, and the Field Geologist helps you reason through what you're looking at — landform identification, evidence of weathering / erosion / deposition, what a stratigraphic exposure might mean, what historical imagery shows about recent change. It will push you to cite specific evidence ("which part of this photo shows that?") before accepting any landscape claim.</p>

<h2>What this partner won't do</h2>
<p>It won't write your Landscape Biography. "Tell me about Marina Beach" gets answered with "what do <em>you</em> notice in this photo — let's start there." It will be honest about ambiguity in field photos (one image rarely shows enough to be sure) and it will push back when you make a more confident claim than the evidence supports. The reject-or-revise move in Block 7's success criteria is the point — you should expect to disagree with the Field Geologist at least once per session.</p>

<h2>Documentation reminder</h2>
<p>Every substantive Field Geologist conversation that feeds into your <a href="/units/unit-2/assessment-landscape-reading/">Landscape Reading</a> gets logged in the <a href="/foundations/ai-documentation-protocol/">AI Documentation Template</a>. The "one thing the AI got wrong" gate applies — find a specific moment where the Field Geologist overstated, misidentified, or guessed.</p>

